{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01JkJeABmS2QkUosJggMGVmB","type":"tool_result","content":"2020\t\t\tdefaultKernel:   []string{\"kernel\", \"kernel-core\", \"kernel-modules\", \"kernel-modules-core\", \"kernel-modules-extra\"},\n2021\t\t\thugePagesKernel: []string{\"kernel-64k-core\", \"kernel-64k-modules\", \"kernel-64k-modules-core\", \"kernel-64k-modules-extra\"},\n2022\t\t\t// Note this list explicitly does *not* include kernel-rt as that is a meta-package that tries to pull in a lot\n2023\t\t\t// of other dependencies we don't want for historical reasons.\n2024\t\t\trealtimeKernel: []string{\"kernel-rt-core\", \"kernel-rt-modules\", \"kernel-rt-modules-extra\"},\n2025\t\t}\n2026\t\treturn kernelPackages\n2027\t}\n2028\t\n2029\t// updateFiles writes files specified by the nodeconfig to disk. it also writes\n2030\t// systemd units. there is no support for multiple filesystems at this point.\n2031\t//\n2032\t// in addition to files, we also write systemd units to disk. we mask, enable,\n2033\t// and disable unit files when appropriate. this function relies on the system\n2034\t// being restarted after an upgrade, so it doesn't daemon-reload or restart\n2035\t// any services.\n2036\t//\n2037\t// it is worth noting that this function explicitly doesn't rely on the ignition\n2038\t// implementation of file, unit writing, enabling or disabling. this is because\n2039\t// ignition is built on the assumption that it is working with a fresh system,\n2040\t// where as we are trying to reconcile a system that has already been running.\n2041\t//\n2042\t// in the future, this function should do any additional work to confirm that\n2043\t// whatever has been written is picked up by the appropriate daemons, if\n2044\t// required. in particular, a daemon-reload and restart for any unit files\n2045\t// touched.\n2046\tfunc (dn *Daemon) updateFiles(oldIgnConfig, newIgnConfig ign3types.Config, addedOrChangedUnits []ign3types.Unit, skipCertificateWrite, forceFilePresent bool) error {\n2047\t\tklog.Info(\"Updating files\")\n2048\t\tif err := dn.writeFiles(newIgnConfig.Storage.Files, skipCertificateWrite); err != nil {\n2049\t\t\treturn err\n2050\t\t}\n2051\t\n2052\t\t// With OCPBUGS-58023, we updated this flow to only write units that were either added or\n2053\t\t// updated. As can be seen in OCPBUGS-74692, this impacted the traditional method to recover\n2054\t\t// from config drifts with systemd units. It makes the `touch /run/machine-config-daemon-force`\n2055\t\t// command useless since the new flow does not rewrite all files, only the ones that have been\n2056\t\t// added or changed with the latest MC. To keep the fix for OCPBUGS-58023 and allow continue\n2057\t\t// supporting the traditional config drift recovery for systemd units, all units should be\n2058\t\t// written when a forcefile exists.\n2059\t\tunitsToWrite := addedOrChangedUnits\n2060\t\tif forceFilePresent {\n2061\t\t\tklog.Info(\"Forcefile exists, writing all units\")\n2062\t\t\tunitsToWrite = newIgnConfig.Systemd.Units\n2063\t\t}\n2064\t\n2065\t\tif err := dn.writeUnits(unitsToWrite); err != nil {\n2066\t\t\treturn err\n2067\t\t}\n2068\t\treturn dn.deleteStaleData(oldIgnConfig, newIgnConfig)\n2069\t}"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01GgWhYnAMaHW3hUb1TwvDza","session_id":"97d67c05-bfc1-43f5-94c6-f2fb356410bf","uuid":"db1302d5-32d7-4af3-bdf6-b23545a2e76c","timestamp":"2026-06-22T21:26:35.046Z","subagent_type":"Explore","task_description":"Research MachineConfig passwd.users and storage.filesystems support"}
