{"type": "assistant", "message": {"model": "claude-sonnet-4-6", "id": "msg_vrtx_016EiChEsThdFkMeXvLnJSTM", "type": "message", "role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "tool_use", "id": "toolu_vrtx_01AeusSyqtSP6VJiX7MvQqR5", "name": "Read", "input": {"file_path": "/home/jsuri/random-testing/prashanth-help/machine-config-operator/docs/MachineConfigDaemon.md"}}], "stop_reason": null, "stop_sequence": null, "stop_details": null, "usage": {"input_tokens": 1, "cache_creation_input_tokens": 1029, "cache_read_input_tokens": 66788, "cache_creation": {"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens": 1029, "ephemeral_1h_input_tokens": 0}, "output_tokens": 21}, "context_management": null}, "parent_tool_use_id": "toolu_vrtx_01GgWhYnAMaHW3hUb1TwvDza", "session_id": "97d67c05-bfc1-43f5-94c6-f2fb356410bf", "uuid": "810976d8-3013-4ffe-8f69-8c030c6212df", "request_id": "req_vrtx_011CcK1QvgVdFhSnh6ShEwc2", "subagent_type": "Explore", "task_description": "Research MachineConfig passwd.users and storage.filesystems support", "timestamp": "2026-06-22T21:28:12.493Z"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01AeusSyqtSP6VJiX7MvQqR5","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# MachineConfigDaemon\n2\t\n3\t## Goals\n4\t\n5\t1. Apply new machine configuration during update.\n6\t\n7\t2. Validate and verify machine's state to the requested machine configuration.\n8\t\n9\t## Non Goals\n10\t\n11\t1. MachineConfigDaemon does not execute scripts on the machines.\n12\t\n13\t## Overview\n14\t\n15\tMachineConfigDaemon is scheduled on the machines in a cluster as a DaemonSet. This daemon is responsible for performing machine updates in OpenShift 4. The update will include tasks related to the systemd units, files on disk, operating system upgrades etc. The MachineConfigDaemon updates a machine to configuration defined by MachineConfig as instructed by the MachineConfigController.\n16\t\n17\tThe MachineConfigDaemon is also responsible for annotating a node with `machineconfiguration.openshift.io/ssh=accessed` when it detects an SSH access to the machine.\n18\t\n19\t## Supported vs Unsupported Ignition config changes\n20\t\n21\tThe MachineConfigDaemon receives machine configuration in the form of a \"rendered\" or merged MachineConfig which is generated from applicable fragments by the controller.\n22\t\n23\tIf the updated Ignition config contains changes compatible with the current config, the node will be updated in place.  Otherwise, it will enter a \"degraded\" state; the idea is that a human or automation tooling can then re-provision degraded machines.\n24\t\n25\tNot all Ignition config sections are supported; see the following table:\n26\t\n27\tIgnition spec 2 sections | Supported\n28\t--- | ---\n29\tFiles | YES\n30\tsystemd Units | YES\n31\tNetworkd | NO\n32\tUsers | NO *\n33\tDirectories | NO\n34\tFileSystems | NO\n35\tLinks | NO\n36\tDisks | NO\n37\tRAID | NO\n38\t\n39\tIgnition spec 3 sections | Supported\n40\t--- | ---\n41\tFiles | YES\n42\tsystemd Units | YES\n43\tUsers | NO *\n44\tGroups | NO\n45\tDirectories | NO\n46\tFileSystems | NO\n47\tLinks | NO\n48\tDisks | NO\n49\tRAID | NO\n50\t\n51\t\\* At this time only updates to `sshAuthorizedKeys` for user `core` are permitted. Please see [Update-SSHKeys](./Update-SSHKeys.md) for details.\n52\t\n53\t## Coordinating updates\n54\t\n55\tThe MachineConfigDaemon uses [annotations defined](./MachineConfigController.md#updatecontroller-interface-with-machineconfigdaemon) on the Node object to coordinate updates with MachineConfigController for the machine.\n56\t\n57\t![MachineConfigDaemon update flow](./MachineConfigDaemonUpdate.svg)\n58\t\n59\t### States\n60\t\n61\t1. `Done` when daemon sets currentConfig = desiredConfig\n62\t\n63\t2. `Working` when daemon starts updating the machine.\n64\t\n65\t3. `Degraded` when daemon cannot continue to apply the update.\n66\t\n67\t## OS updates\n68\t\n69\tIn addition to handling Ignition configs, the MachineConfigDaemon also takes\n70\tcare of updating the base operating system.\n71\t\n72\tUpdates are provided via the `OSImageURL` component of a MachineConfig object.\n73\tThis should generally be controlled by the\n74\t[cluster-version-operator](https://github.com/openshift/cluster-version-operator/),\n75\tand its current existence in MachineConfig objects should be thought of as an\n76\timplementation detail.\n77\t\n78\tMachineConfigDaemon only supports updating Red Hat CoreOS, which uses rpm-ostree.\n79\tThe `OSImageURL` refers to a container image that carries inside it an OSTree payload.  When\n80\tthe `OSImageURL` changes, it will be passed to the [pivot](https://github.com/openshift/pivot)\n81\tcommand which is included in Red Hat CoreOS, and in turn takes care of passing it\n82\tto rpm-ostree.\n83\t\n84\tOnce an update is prepared (in terms of a new bootloader entry which points to a\n85\tnew OSTree \"deployment\" or filesystem tree), then the MachineConfigDaemon will\n86\treboot.\n87\t\n88\t### Verification\n89\t\n90\tUpon start, MachineConfigDaemon queries rpm-ostree to determine the booted system version\n91\tand verifies it matches the expected config.\n92\t\n93\t## systemd unit updates\n94\t\n95\tMachineConfigDaemon replaces the unit service files on disk. The updated systemd services run after machine reboot.\n96\t\n97\tThe daemon should prune all the systemd units that don't exist in the desiredConfig but existed before. Diff the current config and desired config, then remove the units that were removed.\n98\t\n99\t### Verification\n100\t\n101\t1. MachineConfigDaemon verifies that contents and existence of the systemd unit files.\n102\t\n103\t2. MachineConfigDaemon also verifies that the systemd service is enabled when specified in Ignition config.\n104\t\n105\t## Directory / File updates\n106\t\n107\tMachineConfigDaemon replaces the file contents on disk with the contents of the file from the desiredConfig.\n108\t\n109\tThe daemon should apply any change in permissions on file / directories.\n110\t\n111\tThe daemon should prune all the files and directories that don't exist in the desiredConfig but existed before. Diff the current config and desired config, then remove the nodes that were removed.\n112\t\n113\t### Verification\n114\t\n115\tWhen starting, MachineConfigDaemon verifies that contents and existence of the files and directories match the current configuration.  If the MachineConfigDaemon is coming up after applying a \"pending\" configuration, it will become current, and then verification will proceed.\n116\t\n117\t## Machine reboot\n118\t\n119\tWith the exception of [rebootless updates](#rebootless-updates), the MachineConfigDaemon will drain and reboot the machine after applying the updated machine configuration.\n120\t\n121\t## Node drain\n122\t\n123\tThe daemon performs a best-effort node drain before rebooting.\n124\t\n125\tThe node drain behavior:\n126\t\n127\t1. Should not try to remove static pods.\n128\t\n129\t2. Should respect pod disruption policy for evictions.\n130\t\n131\t3. Should not evict pods marked with critical annotation.\n132\t\n133\t4. Should not evict itself from the node.\n134\t\n135\t### Node drain on master nodes\n136\t\n137\tThe draining on master nodes should not be different from worker node as the control plane is self-hosted.\n138\t\n139\t### Node drain master in single master\n140\t\n141\tThe draining of pods on the only master node will not evict the control plane as they have critical pod annotation. After rebooting the only master, the pod-checkpointer brings back the components responsible for restarting the control plane.\n142\t\n143\t### Node drain etcd static pods on masters\n144\t\n145\tEtcd is co-located on master nodes as static pods. The draining behavior defined above prevents draining of static pods to prevent interference to etcd cluster by the daemon.\n146\t\n147\t## Rebootless Updates\n148\t\n149\tAs of Openshift 4.17, the MCO has added a new feature called NodeDisruptionPolicy, which allows the cluster admin to define custom behaviours during MachineConfig updates. The default policies used by NodeDisruptionPolicy reflect the behaviors mentioned below. More details about NodeDisruptionPolicy can be found [here](./NodeDisruptionPolicy.md).\n150\t\n151\tAs of Openshift 4.7, the MCD gained the functionality to apply select MachineConfig updates without a full reboot flow (drain -> update -> reboot). The MCD now calculates a diff between the current and desired configurations, and it uses any changes to select one of the options listed below. For any change not listed below, or if a forcefile was set, the MCD will trigger the full reboot flow.\n152\t\n153\tThe updated list of optimized updates and behaviour (as of Openshift 4.10) is as follows:\n154\t\n155\t### Without Drain\n156\t\n157\tMost reboot exceptions also skip a drain, but some have to reload crio.\n158\t\n159\t#### \"None\" Action\n160\t\n161\tThe \"None\" action only performs the corresponding file write; it does not trigger a drain or a reboot. This action is taken for changes to the following items:\n162\t\n163\t1. [SSH Keys](./Update-SSHKeys.md): updated by changing `ignition.passwd.users.sshAuthorizedKeys` in a MachineConfig\n164\t2. kube-apiserver-to-kubelet-signer CA cert: located at `/etc/kubernetes/kubelet-ca.crt` and autorotated by the openshift-kube-apiserver operator after a 1 year expiry\n165\t3. [Pull Secret](./PullSecret.md): cluster-wide, located at `/var/lib/kubelet/config.json`\n166\t\n167\t#### \"Reload Crio\" Action\n168\t\n169\tThe \"Reload Crio\" action performs the file write and runs a `systemctl reload crio`. It does not trigger a drain or a reboot for changes to the following items:\n170\t\n171\t1. Container signing GPG keys: these can be changed by pointing `/etc/containers/policy.json` to `/etc/machine-config-daemon/no-reboot/containers-gpg.pub` and storing keys in the latter file. Changes to either file trigger the \"Reload Crio\" action\n172\t2. Namespaced containers signing policies: these policy files located under `/etc/crio/policies` directory. Changes to files under this directory trigger the \"Reload Crio\" action\n173\t3. **Selected** `/etc/containers/registries.conf` changes: this file is generally changed via ICSP object changes. Only the following changes will avoid a drain:\n174\t   - addition of a registry with `pull-from-mirror=digest-only` for each mirror\n175\t   - addition of a mirror with `pull-from-mirror=digest-only` in a registry\n176\t   - appending items in the `unqualified-search-registries` list\n177\t\n178\t### With Drain\n179\t\n180\t\"Reload Crio\" is performed with a drain for changes to the following items:\n181\t\n182\t1. **Selected** `/etc/containers/registries.conf` changes: this file is generally changed via ICSP object changes. Node drain will take place except for changes specified [above](#Without-Drain).\n183\t\n184\t## Config Drift Detection\n185\t\n186\t### Overview\n187\t\n188\tThere may be situations when the on-disk state of a node may differ or \"drift\"\n189\tfrom what is specified by the MachineConfig. This is usually (though not\n190\talways) due to a cluster admin manually editing files. In the past, the MCD\n191\twould only verify that the on-disk state matches what is specified by the\n192\tMachineConfig after a reboot. Whenever this occurs, the node and Machine Config\n193\tPool (MCP) would be marked Degraded and unable to apply any MachineConfigs.\n194\t\n195\tBecause reboots do not frequently occur, the config drift isn't immediately\n196\tdetected. In cases where the config drift was intentional, the cluster admin\n197\tmay lose the context which necessitated the config drift between the time the\n198\tdrift occurred and when it was detected. This leads to the node and / or MCP\n199\tbecoming degraded at an inconvenient time and can block future updates until\n200\tthe issue is remedied.\n201\t\n202\t### Detection\n203\t\n204\tTo avoid this, a Config Drift Monitor was built into the MCD in OCP 4.10. It\n205\tuses `fsnotify` to proactively detect config drift and mark the node `Degraded`\n206\twithin seconds of the drift taking place.\n207\t\n208\tWhenever a filesystem write event is detected for any of the objects (Ignition\n209\tfiles and systemd units / dropins) defined in the currently applied\n210\tMachineConfig, the Config Drift Monitor validates that the file contents and\n211\tpermissions fully match what the currently-applied MachineConfig specifies.\n212\t\n213\tWhenever the Config Drift Monitor detects an inconsistent object, it will:\n214\t1. Emit an error to the console logs.\n215\t1. Emit a Kubernetes event indicating that a configuration drift has occurred.\n216\t1. Stop further verification.\n217\t1. Set `machineconfiguration.openshift.io/state` to `Degraded`. \n218\t\n219\t### Machine Config Updates\n220\t\n221\tPrior to applying a new MachineConfig, a preflight check is made to verify that\n222\tthe current on-disk state matches the active MachineConfig. If config drift is\n223\tdetected, `machineconfiguration.openshift.io/state` will be set to `Degraded`\n224\tand the update will not be applied until recovery steps are taken.\n225\t\n226\tTo apply a new MachineConfig, the Config Drift Monitor is temporarily shut down.\n227\tThis is because the config will \"drift\" from the current MachineConfig to the\n228\tnew MachineConfig. Once new MachineConfig has been applied (assuming no reboot\n229\tis needed), the Config Drift Monitor will be restarted and supplied with the\n230\tnewly active MachineConfig. If a reboot is required, the Config Drift Monitor\n231\twill be started once the MCD is out of the booting phase.\n232\t\n233\tWhenever the Config Drift Monitor is started or stopped, a Kubernetes Event\n234\twill be emitted. At startup, the event will also include the name of the\n235\tMachineConfig it is using as a reference.\n236\t\n237\t### Recovering From Config Drift\n238\t\n239\tOnce config drift is detected, there are two options for recovery:\n240\t\n241\t1. Ensure that the contents and file permissons of the file on disk match what\n242\tthe MachineConfig specifies. This can be done by manually rewriting the file\n243\tcontents or changing the file mode. Once this is done, the MCD will reapply the\n244\tcurrent MachineConfig.\n245\t1. Create the forcefile (`/run/machine-config-daemon-force`). This will cause\n246\tthe MCD to bypass the preflight config checks and reapply the current\n247\tMachineConfig. This will also cause the node to reboot, which may not be\n248\tdesirable.\n249\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01GgWhYnAMaHW3hUb1TwvDza","session_id":"97d67c05-bfc1-43f5-94c6-f2fb356410bf","uuid":"1a6b253d-f295-45a5-9c97-c336fddb5890","timestamp":"2026-06-22T21:28:12.494Z","subagent_type":"Explore","task_description":"Research MachineConfig passwd.users and storage.filesystems support"}
