{"type": "assistant", "message": {"model": "claude-sonnet-4-6", "id": "msg_vrtx_018cnSpZXjwWH2bYJ22LzWdB", "type": "message", "role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "tool_use", "id": "toolu_vrtx_01RhaGjpmE9JcehFpZjttukP", "name": "Read", "input": {"file_path": "/home/jsuri/random-testing/prashanth-help/machine-config-operator/docs/Update-SSHKeys.md"}}], "stop_reason": null, "stop_sequence": null, "stop_details": null, "usage": {"input_tokens": 1, "cache_creation_input_tokens": 4268, "cache_read_input_tokens": 67817, "cache_creation": {"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens": 4268, "ephemeral_1h_input_tokens": 0}, "output_tokens": 19}, "context_management": null}, "parent_tool_use_id": "toolu_vrtx_01GgWhYnAMaHW3hUb1TwvDza", "session_id": "97d67c05-bfc1-43f5-94c6-f2fb356410bf", "uuid": "53fe7179-d93c-40de-b456-4254c639b2e7", "request_id": "req_vrtx_011CcK1RDs7CEaGHL3eoG5zk", "subagent_type": "Explore", "task_description": "Research MachineConfig passwd.users and storage.filesystems support", "timestamp": "2026-06-22T21:28:15.038Z"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01RhaGjpmE9JcehFpZjttukP","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Managing SSH Keys with the MCD\n2\t\n3\tBy default, the OpenShift 4 installer creates a single user named `core` (derived in spirit from CoreOS Container Linux) with optional SSH keys specified at install time.\n4\t\n5\tThis controller supports updating the SSH keys of user `core` via a MachineConfig object. The SSH keys are updated for all members of the MachineConfig pool specified in the MachineConfig, for example: all worker nodes.\n6\t\n7\tPlease note that RHCOS nodes will be [annotated](https://github.com/openshift/machine-config-operator/blob/master/docs/MachineConfigDaemon.md#annotating-on-ssh-access) when accessed via SSH.\n8\t\n9\t## Unsupported Operations\n10\t\n11\t- The MCD will not add any new users.\n12\t\n13\t- The MCD will not delete the user `core`.\n14\t\n15\t- The MCD will not make any changes to any other User fields for user `core` other than `sshAuthorizedKeys`.\n16\t\n17\t## Info you will need\n18\t\n19\tYou will need the following information for the MachineConfig that will be used to update your SSHKeys.\n20\t\n21\t- `machineconfiguration.openshift.io/role:` the MachineConfig that is updated will be applied to all nodes with the role specified here. For example: `master` or `worker`\n22\t\n23\t- `sshAuthorizedKeys:` you will need one or more public keys to be assigned to user `core`.  Multiple SSH Keys should begin on different lines and each be preceded by `-`.\n24\t\n25\t## Creating SSH for a pool\n26\t\n27\tIn case your cluster has been installed without providing the ssh key for the `core` user at installation time (verify that `99-worker-ssh`/`99-master-ssh` are missing, by checking `oc get machineconfigs`),\n28\tyou can easily create a MachineConfig that will ship the SSH keys to the nodes in a pool:\n29\t\n30\t```console\n31\t$ cat 99-worker-ssh.yaml\n32\tapiVersion: machineconfiguration.openshift.io/v1\n33\tkind: MachineConfig\n34\tmetadata:\n35\t  labels:\n36\t    machineconfiguration.openshift.io/role: worker\n37\t  name: 99-worker-ssh\n38\tspec:\n39\t  config:\n40\t    ignition:\n41\t      version: 2.2.0\n42\t    passwd:\n43\t      users:\n44\t      - name: core\n45\t        sshAuthorizedKeys:\n46\t        - ssh-rsa ABC123....\n47\t        - ssh-ed25519 XYZ7890....\n48\t```\n49\t\n50\tThen just create the file with `oc`:\n51\t\n52\t```console\n53\t$ oc create -f 99-worker-ssh.yaml\n54\t```\n55\t\n56\tThe MCO will take care of shipping the SSH keys to the nodes in the `worker` pool. The same procedure applies to any other pool in the cluster.\n57\t\n58\t## Updating SSH for workers\n59\t\n60\tList all the machineconfigs currently in the cluster.\n61\t\n62\t```console\n63\t$ oc get machineconfigs\n64\tNAME                                               GENERATEDBYCONTROLLER               IGNITIONVERSION   CREATED\n65\t00-master                                          4.0.0-alpha.0-116-gdc9b354d-dirty   2.2.0             3m40s\n66\t00-worker                                          4.0.0-alpha.0-116-gdc9b354d-dirty   2.2.0             3m40s\n67\t01-master-container-runtime                        4.0.0-alpha.0-116-gdc9b354d-dirty   2.2.0             3m40s\n68\t01-master-kubelet                                  4.0.0-alpha.0-116-gdc9b354d-dirty   2.2.0             3m40s\n69\t01-worker-container-runtime                        4.0.0-alpha.0-116-gdc9b354d-dirty   2.2.0             3m39s\n70\t01-worker-kubelet                                  4.0.0-alpha.0-116-gdc9b354d-dirty   2.2.0             3m39s\n71\t99-master-ssh                                                                          2.2.0             3m57s\n72\t99-worker-ssh                                                                          2.2.0             3m56s\n73\trendered-master-753f1b4476475611360ba65b4d0d378d   4.0.0-alpha.0-116-gdc9b354d-dirty   2.2.0             3m36s\n74\trendered-worker-6a77758776c24585f8db809b64569b6f   4.0.0-alpha.0-116-gdc9b354d-dirty   2.2.0             3m36s\n75\t```\n76\t\n77\t`99-worker-ssh` contains the current SSHAuthorizedKeys for `worker` pool.\n78\t\n79\t```console\n80\t$ oc get machineconfigs 99-worker-ssh -oyaml\n81\tapiVersion: machineconfiguration.openshift.io/v1\n82\tkind: MachineConfig\n83\tmetadata:\n84\t  labels:\n85\t    machineconfiguration.openshift.io/role: worker\n86\t  name: 99-worker-ssh\n87\tspec:\n88\t  config:\n89\t    ignition:\n90\t      version: 2.2.0\n91\t    passwd:\n92\t      users:\n93\t      - name: core\n94\t        sshAuthorizedKeys:\n95\t        - ssh-rsa ABC123....\n96\t        - ssh-ed25519 XYZ7890....\n97\t        - ecdsa-sha2-nistp256 AAAAE2....\n98\t```\n99\t\n100\tExport the `99-worker-ssh` to edit the `SSHAuthorizedKeys`.\n101\t\n102\t```sh\n103\toc get machineconfigs 99-worker-ssh -oyaml > update-ssh-worker.yaml\n104\t```\n105\t\n106\tUpdate the `sshAuthorizedKeys` for `core` user in `update-ssh-worker.yaml`.\n107\t\n108\t```yaml\n109\t# update-ssh-worker.yaml\n110\tapiVersion: machineconfiguration.openshift.io/v1\n111\tkind: MachineConfig\n112\tmetadata:\n113\t  labels:\n114\t    machineconfiguration.openshift.io/role: worker\n115\t  name: 99-worker-ssh\n116\tspec:\n117\t  config:\n118\t    ignition:\n119\t      version: 2.2.0\n120\t    passwd:\n121\t      users:\n122\t      - name: core\n123\t        sshAuthorizedKeys:\n124\t        - ssh rsa ABC123....\n125\t        - ssh rsa XYZ7890....\n126\t```\n127\t\n128\tNow with your MachineConfig yaml file (using the example above), apply the changes.\n129\t\n130\t```sh\n131\toc apply -f update-ssh-worker.yaml\n132\t```\n133\t\n134\tYou should see the new MachineConfig being generated by the controller to roll the changes:\n135\t\n136\t```console\n137\t$ oc get machineconfigs\n138\tNAME                                               GENERATEDBYCONTROLLER               IGNITIONVERSION   CREATED\n139\t00-master                                          4.0.0-alpha.0-116-gdc9b354d-dirty   2.2.0             3m40s\n140\t00-worker                                          4.0.0-alpha.0-116-gdc9b354d-dirty   2.2.0             3m40s\n141\t01-master-container-runtime                        4.0.0-alpha.0-116-gdc9b354d-dirty   2.2.0             3m40s\n142\t01-master-kubelet                                  4.0.0-alpha.0-116-gdc9b354d-dirty   2.2.0             3m40s\n143\t01-worker-container-runtime                        4.0.0-alpha.0-116-gdc9b354d-dirty   2.2.0             3m39s\n144\t01-worker-kubelet                                  4.0.0-alpha.0-116-gdc9b354d-dirty   2.2.0             3m39s\n145\t99-master-ssh                                                                          2.2.0             3m57s\n146\t99-worker-ssh                                                                          2.2.0             3m56s\n147\trendered-master-753f1b4476475611360ba65b4d0d378d   4.0.0-alpha.0-116-gdc9b354d-dirty   2.2.0             3m36s\n148\trendered-worker-6a77758776c24585f8db809b64569b6f   4.0.0-alpha.0-116-gdc9b354d-dirty   2.2.0             3m36s\n149\trendered-worker-21612112efc1dde979f1c73c1d9df168   4.0.0-alpha.0-116-gdc9b354d-dirty   2.2.0             10s\n150\t```\n151\t\n152\tYou are then able to monitor the MCD logs of a worker or master (whichever the config applied to), which should check the proposed changes and reboot into the new config:\n153\t\n154\t```sh\n155\toc logs -f -n openshift-machine-config-operator machine-config-daemon-<hash>\n156\t```\n157\t\n158\tIf the update was succesfully applied, you should expect to see lines similar to in these logs:\n159\t\n160\t```console\n161\tI0111 19:59:07.360110    7993 update.go:258] SSH Keys reconcilable\n162\t...\n163\tI0111 19:59:07.371253    7993 update.go:569] Writing SSHKeys at \"/home/core/.ssh\"\n164\t...\n165\tI0111 19:59:07.372208    7993 update.go:613] machine-config-daemon initiating reboot: Node will reboot into config worker-96b48815fa067f651fa50541ea6a9b5d\n166\t```\n167\t\n168\tAfter the node reboots, expect to see the daemons for the node specified restarted:\n169\t\n170\t```console\n171\t$ oc get pods -n openshift-machine-config-operator\n172\t\n173\tNAME                                         READY     STATUS    RESTARTS   AGE\n174\tmachine-config-controller-68f5989588-2cfvq   1/1       Running   0          1h\n175\tmachine-config-daemon-58d6c                  1/1       Running   0          1h\n176\tmachine-config-daemon-c7jkk                  1/1       Running   1          1h\n177\tmachine-config-daemon-ddsnp                  1/1       Running   1          1h\n178\tmachine-config-daemon-kx49n                  1/1       Running   1          1h\n179\tmachine-config-daemon-q8d7j                  1/1       Running   0          1h\n180\tmachine-config-daemon-w68t9                  1/1       Running   0          1h\n181\tmachine-config-operator-769967ddf5-9blb8     1/1       Running   0          1h\n182\tmachine-config-server-7gckv                  1/1       Running   0          1h\n183\tmachine-config-server-98cpz                  1/1       Running   0          1h\n184\tmachine-config-server-pzj68                  1/1       Running   0          1h\n185\t```\n186\t\n187\tIf we check the same daemon's logs, we should now see similar lines in the output:\n188\t\n189\t```console\n190\t$ oc logs -f -n openshift-machine-config-operator machine-config-daemon-<same-hash>\n191\t\n192\t...\n193\tI0111 20:00:15.755052    6900 daemon.go:497] Completing pending config worker-52df682dc5cb3976b063ef3f197ead5e\n194\t...\n195\tI0111 20:00:15.769349    6900 update.go:613] machine-config-daemon: completed update for config worker-52df682dc5cb3976b063ef3f197ead5e\n196\t...\n197\tI0111 20:00:15.778909    6900 daemon.go:503] In desired config worker-52df682dc5cb3976b063ef3f197ead5e\n198\t```\n199\t\n200\t## Common Pitfalls\n201\t\n202\t- Updating `user: name`: Do not update the `user: name` field. The only user currently supported is `core` as shown in the above example config.\n203\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01GgWhYnAMaHW3hUb1TwvDza","session_id":"97d67c05-bfc1-43f5-94c6-f2fb356410bf","uuid":"2505596d-caec-4e58-8b7b-037c22dbf1dc","timestamp":"2026-06-22T21:28:15.039Z","subagent_type":"Explore","task_description":"Research MachineConfig passwd.users and storage.filesystems support"}
