{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01GgWhYnAMaHW3hUb1TwvDza","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Here is the complete, thorough report on all four questions.\n\n---\n\n## 1. `passwd.users` — In-Place Update Support and Caveats\n\n### What is supported\n\nIn-place updates to `passwd.users` are strictly limited. The `isConfigReconcilable` function in `/home/jsuri/random-testing/prashanth-help/machine-config-operator/pkg/controller/common/reconcile.go` (lines 101–109) gates all passwd changes through `validatePasswdChanges`.\n\n`validatePasswdChanges` (lines 196–219) enforces three rules:\n\n1. **No changes to `Passwd.Groups` are permitted** (line 197).\n2. **Only the user named `\"core\"` is permitted in `Passwd.Users`** (lines 204–207). Any non-core user causes an immediate reconcilable error: `\"ignition passwd user section contains unsupported changes: non-core user\"`.\n3. **For the `core` user, only `SSHAuthorizedKeys` and `PasswordHash` fields may be set** — all other fields on `PasswdUser` must be empty. This is enforced by `verifyUserFields` (lines 177–192), which blanks those two fields and does a `reflect.DeepEqual` against an empty struct. If anything else (e.g., `HomeDir`, `Shell`, `Groups`) is non-zero, it returns: `\"SSH keys and password hash are not reconcilable\"`.\n\nThe official documentation at `/home/jsuri/random-testing/prashanth-help/machine-config-operator/docs/MachineConfigDaemon.md` (lines 43–51) states plainly:\n\n> Users | NO \\*\n> \\* At this time only updates to `sshAuthorizedKeys` for user `core` are permitted.\n\nAnd `/home/jsuri/random-testing/prashanth-help/machine-config-operator/docs/Update-SSHKeys.md` (lines 9–15) says:\n\n> - The MCD will not add any new users.\n> - The MCD will not delete the user `core`.\n> - The MCD will not make any changes to any other User fields for user `core` other than `sshAuthorizedKeys`.\n\nNote that `passwordHash` is also handled at runtime (see `SetPasswordHash` in `update.go` lines 2572–2614), and the `verifyUserFields` function does permit it alongside `SSHAuthorizedKeys`. So `passwordHash` for user `core` is in practice also updated in-place, even though the docs only mention SSH keys.\n\n### Critical caveat: adding users is explicitly blocked\n\n`updateSSHKeys` and `SetPasswordHash` in `/home/jsuri/random-testing/prashanth-help/machine-config-operator/pkg/daemon/update.go` both contain this guard (lines 2582–2586 and 2648–2651):\n\n```go\ncase errors.As(err, &uErr):\n    klog.Info(\"core user does not exist, and creating users is not supported, so ignoring configuration specified for core user\")\n    return nil\n```\n\nThe reconcile check at the render-controller layer already blocks non-core users before they even reach the daemon. So:\n\n- **Adding new users via `passwd.users` is completely unsupported** — it will be rejected at reconcile time as irreconcilable.\n- **Changing fields other than `sshAuthorizedKeys` / `passwordHash` for `core` is unsupported** — same rejection path.\n- **Changes to `passwd.groups` are unsupported**.\n\nThe `machineConfigDiff` struct (line 1499) tracks `passwd bool`, and it is set (line 1562) any time `oldIgn.Passwd != newIgn.Passwd`. When set, only SSH key and password hash operations are performed (lines 1222–1266). There is no code path in `update.go` that calls `useradd` or otherwise creates a user.\n\n---\n\n## 2. `storage.filesystems` — In-Place Update Support and Caveats\n\n### Filesystems are irreconcilable by default\n\nThe `isConfigReconcilable` function at lines 129–132 of `/home/jsuri/random-testing/prashanth-help/machine-config-operator/pkg/controller/common/reconcile.go`:\n\n```go\nif !slices.Contains(storageOverrides, opv1.IrreconcilableValidationOverridesStorageFileSystems) &&\n    !reflect.DeepEqual(oldIgn.Storage.Filesystems, newIgn.Storage.Filesystems) {\n    return fmt.Errorf(\"ignition filesystems section contains changes\")\n}\n```\n\nAny change to `storage.filesystems` between the old and new rendered config is rejected as irreconcilable unless a special override is present (see below). The same applies to `storage.disks` and `storage.raid`.\n\nThe `updateFiles` function comment at line 2030 in `/home/jsuri/random-testing/prashanth-help/machine-config-operator/pkg/daemon/update.go` says:\n\n```go\n// systemd units. there is no support for multiple filesystems at this point.\n```\n\nAnd `docs/MachineConfigDaemon.md` confirms (lines 34 and 46):\n\n> FileSystems | NO (for both Ignition spec 2 and spec 3)\n\nThe `machineConfigDiff` struct does not even contain a `filesystems` field — the daemon does not track or act on filesystem changes in any way during in-place updates.\n\n### The `IrreconcilableValidationOverrides` escape hatch\n\nThere is a newer mechanism, `IrreconcilableValidationOverrides`, which can suppress the reconcilable check for `storage.filesystems` (and `storage.disks`, `storage.raid`). When enabled, the check is bypassed and the new config is accepted, but the MCD itself still does not apply the filesystem changes to the running node — it just doesn't reject them. The `irreconcilableDifferencesReportGeneratorImpl` in `/home/jsuri/random-testing/prashanth-help/machine-config-operator/pkg/daemon/irreconcilable_diff_reporter.go` (line 151) then reports the filesystem delta to `MachineConfigNode.status.irreconcilableChanges` for observability. The intended use case is for newly provisioned nodes to pick up the disk/filesystem config at install time.\n\nThe e2e test in `/home/jsuri/random-testing/prashanth-help/machine-config-operator/test/extended-priv/mco_storage.go` (lines 602–609) demonstrates this: existing nodes get `spec.config.storage.filesystems` reported as irreconcilable, while newly provisioned nodes with the right hardware will boot clean.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Real Example MachineConfig YAML Files\n\n### Example 1: `passwd.users` with SSH keys (bootstrap testdata)\n\n`/home/jsuri/random-testing/prashanth-help/machine-config-operator/pkg/controller/bootstrap/testdata/bootstrap/99_openshift-machineconfig_master.yaml`\n\n```yaml\napiVersion: machineconfiguration.openshift.io/v1\nkind: MachineConfig\nmetadata:\n  labels:\n    machineconfiguration.openshift.io/role: master\n  name: 99-master-ssh\nspec:\n  config:\n    ignition:\n      version: 3.2.0\n    passwd:\n      users:\n      - name: core\n        sshAuthorizedKeys:\n        - ssh-rsa SSH-AUTHORIZED-KEY\n    storage: {}\n    systemd: {}\n  osImageURL: \"\"\n```\n\nThe worker equivalent is at `/home/jsuri/random-testing/prashanth-help/machine-config-operator/pkg/controller/bootstrap/testdata/bootstrap/99_openshift-machineconfig_worker.yaml` with `role: worker` and `name: 99-worker-ssh`.\n\n### Example 2: `storage.filesystems` with disk/raid (test template)\n\n`/home/jsuri/random-testing/prashanth-help/machine-config-operator/test/extended-priv/testdata/files/extra-disks.yaml`\n\n```yaml\napiVersion: template.openshift.io/v1\nkind: Template\n...\nspec:\n  config:\n    ignition:\n      version: 3.5.0\n    storage:\n      disks:\n      - device: ${DEVICE1}\n        wipeTable: true\n        partitions:\n        - label: raid.1.1\n          number: 1\n          sizeMiB: 1024\n          startMiB: 0\n      raid:\n      - devices:\n        - \"/dev/disk/by-partlabel/raid.1.1\"\n        - \"/dev/disk/by-partlabel/raid.1.2\"\n        level: stripe\n        name: data\n      filesystems:\n      - device: \"/dev/md/data\"\n        path: \"/var/lib/data\"\n        format: ext4\n        label: DATA\n```\n\n### Example 3: From the SSH key update docs\n\n`/home/jsuri/random-testing/prashanth-help/machine-config-operator/docs/Update-SSHKeys.md` (lines 31–48) shows the canonical minimal form:\n\n```yaml\napiVersion: machineconfiguration.openshift.io/v1\nkind: MachineConfig\nmetadata:\n  labels:\n    machineconfiguration.openshift.io/role: worker\n  name: 99-worker-ssh\nspec:\n  config:\n    ignition:\n      version: 2.2.0\n    passwd:\n      users:\n      - name: core\n        sshAuthorizedKeys:\n        - ssh-rsa ABC123....\n        - ssh-ed25519 XYZ7890....\n```\n\nNote the docs example still uses `2.2.0` — but any version the MCO accepts (2.2 through 3.5) will be converted internally to 3.5.0. For new configs, use `3.5.0`.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Ignition Spec Version Targeted by MCO\n\nThe MCO's internal canonical version is **3.5.0**, set as the constant:\n\n`/home/jsuri/random-testing/prashanth-help/machine-config-operator/pkg/controller/common/constants.go`, line 110:\n\n```go\nInternalMCOIgnitionVersion = \"3.5.0\"\n```\n\nThe comment (lines 105–109) explains the intent: all configs are converted to this version internally regardless of what version was submitted.\n\nThe `NewIgnConfig()` helper at `/home/jsuri/random-testing/prashanth-help/machine-config-operator/pkg/controller/common/helpers.go` line 285 uses `ign3types.MaxVersion.String()`, which resolves to `3.5.0` from the vendor package at `/home/jsuri/random-testing/prashanth-help/machine-config-operator/vendor/github.com/coreos/ignition/v2/config/v3_5/types/config.go` (lines 27–30):\n\n```go\nMaxVersion = semver.Version{\n    Major: 3,\n    Minor: 5,\n}\n```\n\nThe ignition converter in `/home/jsuri/random-testing/prashanth-help/machine-config-operator/pkg/controller/common/ignition_converter.go` supports bidirectional conversion between versions 2.2, 3.1, 3.2, 3.3, 3.4, and 3.5. When users submit a config with `version: 3.2.0` (as seen in the bootstrap testdata YAMLs) or even `version: 2.2.0` (as seen in the docs), it is automatically converted to 3.5.0 for internal processing. For new MachineConfigs, you should specify `version: 3.5.0`.\n\n---\n\n## Summary Table\n\n| Field | In-place update supported? | Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| `passwd.users[].sshAuthorizedKeys` (core only) | YES, no reboot | Only user `core`, only this field plus `passwordHash` |\n| `passwd.users[].passwordHash` (core only) | YES, with reboot | Permitted by `verifyUserFields` alongside SSH keys |\n| `passwd.users` — adding new users | NO | Rejected at reconcile: `\"non-core user\"` |\n| `passwd.users` — other fields (HomeDir, Shell…) | NO | Rejected: `\"SSH keys and password hash are not reconcilable\"` |\n| `passwd.groups` | NO | Rejected: `\"ignition Passwd Groups section contains changes\"` |\n| `storage.filesystems` | NO (in-place) | Rejected: `\"ignition filesystems section contains changes\"` — only apply-on-new-node via `IrreconcilableValidationOverrides` |\n| `storage.disks` | NO (in-place) | Same as filesystems |\n| `storage.raid` | NO (in-place) | Same as filesystems |\n| Ignition version targeted | **3.5.0** | All versions 2.2–3.5 accepted and converted |"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"97d67c05-bfc1-43f5-94c6-f2fb356410bf","uuid":"1b3a7299-3e6c-46b3-9d1e-43f07f2d558d","timestamp":"2026-06-22T21:29:17.856Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"In the machine-config-operator repository at /home/jsuri/random-testing/prashanth-help/machine-config-operator, I need to understand:\n\n1. How `passwd.users` is handled by the MachineConfigDaemon — specifically, does in-place update support adding users? Look for any caveats, warnings, or \"not supported\" comments around passwd/user handling in the daemon code.\n2. How `storage.filesystems` is handled — does in-place update support creating new filesystems? Look for any warnings or limitations.\n3. Find 2-3 real example MachineConfig YAML files (in tests, docs, or examples directories) that show passwd.users or storage.filesystems usage so I can see the correct schema.\n4. What Ignition spec version (e.g., 3.2, 3.4) the MCO currently targets.\n\nSearch breadth: very thorough. Focus on: pkg/daemon/, vendor/github.com/coreos/ignition, test/e2e/, and any docs/ or examples/ directories. Report file paths and line numbers for key findings.","agentId":"a5cba4a548698d94a","agentType":"Explore","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Here i